< Review>
Bars with pool tables in Pasadena CA has to be R Place. When you enter you will be met by Jackie. Fantastic bartender with a great sense of humor. She is really good at making everyone feel at home. R Place is a local dive bar with everything a good dive bar would have. This is my go to place when I am in Pasadena. Thanks for a really good time R Place.</Review>

< text>
Soo Good is Sooooo Good! I have been here three times in the last few weeks since the new owner took over (her name is Teresita, btw). Every time I've come here, it's been fantastic. The food is always fresh, the service is always friendly, and the restaurant is spotless. I take the food to go, and eat it at work. I didn't know much about Filipino cuisine, and I was a little intimidated at first, but if you ask nicely they'll let you try a sample. In the past I've ordered the pork, chicken, egg rolls (amazing) and rice. The pork is succulent and sweet, and I don't know how they cook it but it melts off the bone. If you've never tried Filipino food, it's worth trying it out and eating some fresh, home-cooked fare. I wish I could give this place ten stars, I plan to go back on a regular basis. ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Great experience!< /text>

<user_name>Dann Mallet<//user_name><review>Yum! A good selection of filipino dishes waiting to be dished up from the hot box. We went twice for breakfast (although non-breakfast dishes also seem to be available all day too).

I had tocilog and it was the most massive breakfast ever. Two fried eggs, a huge lump of garlic rice and a massive serve of tocino, for I think about $5.50. We also tried the pork bbq (really good).

Coffee was free and serve yourself (although we didn't have any). The place itself doesn't look fancy (but it would be weird if it did), and the staff and customers alike were all fairly noisy talking to each other from front to back of the restaurant... so pretty standard filipino behaviour :P<//review>< Response>

<user_name>June Mathis<//user_name><Time>1433747803943</Time><user_id>106380934947694056688< /user_id>< review>
This place is located in a small shopping complex with blockbuster videos, red ribbon bakery, flower shop, and Iittle caesars pizza... Awesome Filipino comfort food.. The wifey ordered fried galunggong(fried fish) and veggies..

I ordered the beef asado(sweet flavored sauce) and 4 shumais.. For dessert we shared a small cup of ginataan (coconut based dessert with sugar, tapioca, plantains, jackfruit, and taro dough balls), best when served hot or warm..

There are other food selections to choose from like the breakfast menu: tapsilog(crispy fried beef), longsilog(sweet sausages) and many more.. Tastes like homemade food (Mmmm). When you order TOGO, they give you enough food for the whole day..

They do catering on large orders for parties.. Location is good since you can see it right away when you pass by.. Parking is plenty..

There's no service, it's like going to Panda Express.. Limited seating but you can always order takeout..< /review>

<Review>This was our first ti.e camping here. There are 3 different types of campsites: regular, premium, RV hookup. We went with the regular site for $35. It wasnt bad.

We had to move the wooden picnic table so our tent could fit on the grassy area and not on the concrete driveway.. so that's a negative.

We got to hear the ocean all day/night long!! <3 It was a short little hike from.the campsite to the beach area. It's a steep hill, so take your time and watch out to not fall or fall.off the side since it's more or less a cliff.

Theres coin operated showers, flushable toilets, and 1 sink on the side if building to brush your teeth,  and 1 larger sink that allows warm water for washing dishes.

Theres wifi.

They allow dogs.

They provide a food box, in which you will NEED to use. Theres skunks and raccoons that will get into your stuff like they did with ours on the first night.

They sell a bundle of firewood for $10 a bundle, with kindling. The fire rings are kinda high so it's hard to sit in your chairs to get warm from the fire.

Places such as Capitola is less than 10 mins away by car.

This is a good place to camp with children. We saw many with their bikes and skateboards riding around. This camp ground has a nice skate/bike park just out front of it.

Overall, this is a great campground and we will be returning to it.< /Review>< date>

New Brighton is an okay Beach but if I'm going to go to the beach I'm going to go to Rio del Mar esplanade.it's really the same Beach but it is more to the center of the area and there are services there like a restaurant, a coffee shop, a bar and a deli and lots of parking. Plus you have the choice of walking on the beach or taking the 1-mile pathway adjacent to the Beach to the right. Facing the ocean you can drive down to the left to the extension Beach and past that there is no enforcement for dog leash rules and you can walk for miles down to seascape & beyond.<//text>

< Review>
Tent camper in a premium bluff site across from me was using a porta-pottie in their tent. Saw them dump their human waste over the fence down the bluff 4 times in two days.

Generators running till 1030pm. Be ready for typical summer "campers" with no respect for park or their neighbors.

General maintenance is worst I've seen in last 15 years. Restrooms look like they haven't been cleaned in 6 months. Toilets and sinks are full of black mold. Bottoms of toilet seats caked with feces. I was here 7 weeks ago and it's gotten worse.
Bring what you need to prevent infectious diseases..
beach is nice.<//Review>

<Date>1536278208131< /Date><rate>4<//rate>< Review>
My overall experience with VU has been great. I was pre-approved even with forced bankruptcy less than 4 years ago, due to military disabilities. The loan process went smoothly, the team was very patient with me despite focusing on health issues and doctor appointments, and were very cheerful and helpful. I am disappointed that after only few weeks of closing, my loan was already sold to another lender. Hmmm...Few questions ran through my mind regarding this. I would recommend asking your loan officer about this.</Review>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Resp>
{'time': 1536690021843, 'text': "Hi Marie, thank you for sharing your feedback, and I am certainly sorry to hear about your frustrations.\n\nWe aren't yet set up to keep all loans for the long term, though we are working towards that goal, and in the meantime, we only work with servicers that we have a good working relationship with, which allows us to work together in case of any concerns regarding your loan. A loan servicing transfer in no way is a reflection on your loan or how much we value you as a customer of Veterans United Home Loans.\n\nWe understand there can be questions surrounding a loan transfer to a new company, and we want to emphasize that Veterans United staff are still here to support you with assistance if needed. If you have any concerns, please let us know! Our customer service supervisors can answer questions and concerns regarding a loan servicing transfer at 1-800-212-5200 or ClientAdvocate@veteransunited.com."}<//Resp>

Lizzie Jimenez<//name>
<Date>1583904635611</Date><Rating>5< /Rating><Review>Great fun! My partner and I are young adults and we had a blast! We went at 6pm (right when they opened) on a Tuesday and we basically had the place to ourselves. The staff is very friendly, very informed, and went above and beyond to make sure we had the best experience. The front desk worker offered to hold my bag of books (we had gone to The Book Loft beforehand and we also did not rent a car for our visit) and the Boxcar Cafe worker gladly checked the ingredients lists for allergens. (The BBQ sauce does contain dairy.)

We did the Assassin's Creed experience room first thing, and it was AMAZING. If you're a fan of the games, you should definitely include this in your itinerary. It was the most expensive experience room at $60 ($30 each), but so worth it. The other games were engaging and we easily spent 4 hours and $100 (including the Assassin's Creed room but not the snacks), and we are two adults in our 20's.

We got the kettle chip chicken nuggets with BBQ, a bottle of water, and 2 scoops of ice cream which came out to just under $20. The food is delicious and definitely worth the price (although $4 for a bottle of water is a little crazy...there are water fountains available.)

This was a highlight of our trip and we will be talking about this for ages!</Review>< pics>

< text>
Two Bit Circus was a really fun experience.  It felt like a more arcade-heavy gaming experience than going to Dave & Buster's and and it didn't have that 'casino' feel of "how much can I win from this place".  Instead it focuses on people having fun though gaming, and that transcends digital gaming.  There's giant Jenga blocks and giant connect 4 gaming boards upstairs.  It also included a selection of story rooms which feel like an escape room.  A bunch of people go in and try to beat the game in a room (VERY cooperation heavy).  More digital than the typical escape room which made it very interesting.  We also had a personal bar and catering.  Food was great!  All and all great experience!< /text>

<rate>5< /rate><Name>Brian Ellis<//Name><GmapID>0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02</GmapID>< text>
Hard to wrap your head around by just the website description, but Two Bit Circus is basically:

A pretty good bar
A counter with quick bites (fries and hot dogs)
Arcade with a points card
Physical arcade (skeeball type stuff)
VR arcade
VR "experiences"
Escape/story rooms

...all of which is a surprisingly good price relative to other places. Main novelties include a robot bartender, a killer queen cabinet, and a private area for group reservations. Insanely busy on weekends, but perfectly manageable on weekdays.<//text>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02<//Gmap_id><review>Hard to wrap your head around by just the website description, but Two Bit Circus is basically:

A pretty good bar
A counter with quick bites (fries and hot dogs)
Arcade with a points card
Physical arcade (skeeball type stuff)
VR arcade
VR "experiences"
Escape/story rooms

...all of which is a surprisingly good price relative to other places. Main novelties include a robot bartender, a killer queen cabinet, and a private area for group reservations. Insanely busy on weekends, but perfectly manageable on weekdays.</review><userid>109614450247068327429</userid><time>1567724527525<//time></record>

<user_name>Spiro Bogdanos</user_name>< Date>
1559802426788</Date>
<Rating>4</Rating>< review>
Awesome arcade for adult kids-at-heart. Amazing Virtual Reality attractions, I loved the VR maze. On the down side, there is very little parking here. The VR experiences prices, as of this posting, range from $7 to $15 depending on duration and equipment required. I feel like some are very fair, while others a bit overpriced. I would like to see an option to buy an unlimited day pass for VR attractions. Overall this place is a ton of fun, amazing display of VR technology, and good value because most of the regular arcade games are pretty cheap. I hope that this place stays around for a long time and continues to push the boundaries of technology in entertainment.<//review>

<text>My first time and I am IMPRESSED! While I went solo, this is definitely geared towards groups or at least couples with a lot of the games being unplayable by yourself. Knowing that, there are games for solo stars, and there are games for all skill levels.

The food and drinks (including at the bar) are reasonably priced, like way better than at a traditional amusement park, but they get even better with Happy Hour and the accompanying combo deala.

Definitely mark this spot for your next special occassion or staycation, it's fun for HOURS!<//text>< Pictures>

<rating>5</rating>< Review>
My first time and I am IMPRESSED! While I went solo, this is definitely geared towards groups or at least couples with a lot of the games being unplayable by yourself. Knowing that, there are games for solo stars, and there are games for all skill levels.

The food and drinks (including at the bar) are reasonably priced, like way better than at a traditional amusement park, but they get even better with Happy Hour and the accompanying combo deala.

Definitely mark this spot for your next special occassion or staycation, it's fun for HOURS!< /Review>

<Review>Cool place!< /Review><UserId.>103612208227581977669< /UserId.></record></dataset><record>

<UserId.>118193613327214037093</UserId.>< gmapID>
0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02</gmapID>
<text>- B R E A K D O W N (# of + stars = rating)
* A T M O S P H E R E/C O N C E P T: +1 star
* F O O D/P R E S E N T A T I O N: +1 star
* P O R T I O N/C O S T: +1 star
* S E R V I C E: +1 star
* R E V I S I T: -1 star

I actually had a blast here... lmao! It's a 3D amusement park with lots of colors, sounds, and games! The concept is great, the games were fun, everyone was friendly and the games aren't terribly priced. I did come with a large group of people (15+ people) that know how to have fun :D!

The one thing they could have done better was allow reservations to be done in person instead of online. EVERYTHING was booked by the time we got there to try the place out. I feel as if these arcades are best done spontaneously than having it all planned out amongst friends. It doesn't benefit people that want to come in for a few hours randomly. You'll get the most out of it by planning ahead... but it sucks if you're randomly in the area and want to kill time.

I probably won't go again unless I plan it out but that probably means I won't make it back since I won't think to ever plan ahead. AND this was on a WEEKDAY, so it would be all booked on a weekend as well. Hence the minus star for the revisit even though I think the place is pretty fun - think about how much more fun it could have been if we were able to try all the stuff that was booked though... O_O!

I didn't try the drinks or food but the bartenders were excellent at giving me water when I needed it, so much love for that.

Random FYI: It was also neck brace friendly for a lot of the games. I had a pinched nerve and could still play the maze and a lot of the games while wearing it.

In addition, their staff is just cool and very energetic even when they were closing. :)

P A R K I N G

They have a small lot next to the arcade but you might find some on the street near by or at the old Museum of Ice Cream (pink building) if you don't mind a small hike.<//text>< Rate>
4< /Rate>

Ben Jacoby</name>

1569288268891</date>
< rate>
5< /rate>
<review>This place is definitely one of a kind when it comes to entertainment in Los Angeles. At first, you kind of do not know where to start, after a quick stroll is pretty clear where to start. Some of the attractions require to schedule therefore Iowa recommend to walk around a bit and see what you're interested in first. The prices for the attractions are definitely on the higher side, but it is important to distinguish what is expensive for no reason versus expensive but worth it. This place is expensive but worth it. You do not have to spend $100's to have a great experience, but this place definitely has lots of options to bounce from one to another. As someone who never  considered himself as a gamer I really enjoyed the virtual reality experiences. There is one ride where you are basically buckled into a bird like machine and you are experiencing flight  in VR - I would highly recommend you do this if you are here. The restroom was very clean, The bar had great drinks with a happy hour with a good options. I would definitely go again and bring people from out of town to see what the city has the offer.< /review>< Pics>

<user_id>108824989324553939854</user_id><username>Katharine Robinson< /username>< time>
1581611247616</time>
< rate>
2</rate>
< review>
So the ONLY reason they are getting 2 stars is because some of the games are really cool. If you were going on a normal day with a few friends at non-peak hours, you would probably have a great time.

However, my company held our Christmas party there and it was a nightmare.  They were given our numbers in advance (we had somewhere between 2-300) and the food was just an utter disaster.  The line went out the door, and several dozen people didn't get any at all after standing in line for OVER THREE HOURS.  When I had mine they were already slicing the portions... The mac n cheese on my plate was 2 very small bites, the cornbread the servers were cutting in half from what a portion would have been, so really I only got half a meal as was. I can't even imagine how many people wouldn't have eaten if people were getting the amount of food they had paid for!

Not only was there not enough food by far, but the set up for it was atrocious. There was only one line (for all several hundred of us) but there was no runner for the line, meaning that if any server in the line ran out of their tray, or even normal things like napkins, the entire line shut down as we all waited for them to go and get whatever it was and come back. Just a disaster.  Our party committee asked Two Bit for some kind of compensation, and it was a fight to get it... first they were told our employees must have gone through multiple times and gotten seconds. In a three hour line?? Shove off.  We finally received something, and those who didn't eat received their money back.

On a normal day, I *might* be convinced to go back there, though I'd be wary as hell. And if any group with a large party is considering paying Two Bit to host-  DON'T.< /review>

<user>112098878254984727149< /user><username>Daniel Hirsch</username>< Date>
1579754129308< /Date>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
<Review>Two Bit Circus is an impressive venue with a lot of unique (one-of-a-kind) games and attractions on the midway, cool VR and story room experiences and decent food and beverage offerings. The staff are friendly and professional and the venue is well-maintained.

I was the host for our company outing with a group of 80. Our event organizers (Dustin and his boss, Shari) were somewhat helpful, but I didn't genuinely feel like my business (a check of almost $6k) was appreciated; kind of taken for granted. I felt like I had to make all of the contact with the venue to finalize contracts, headcount and lead them through the details of our event. Perhaps a group of 80 is too "small potatoes??"

We wanted to spend more, but Two Bit Circus absolutely wouldn't compromise on additional spend for the premium VR or story room experiences from their retail pricing on a slow Thursday night.

Nevertheless, our group had a good time with the taco bar setup ($34/person) which included soft drinks and 3 hours of midway play (most games.) The food was just adequate - nothing special, but kept running out during meal service so the kitchen scrambled to prepare more. Games were great, VR experiences were also a lot of fun.

Would return, but wouldn't rush back. Hopefully they take the post-event feedback I shared seriously as I never heard back on any of it.< /Review><Pics>None</Pics><Response>None<//Response>< gmapID>

<Review>Two Bit Circus is pretty much an enhanced dave and busters. There are games to play and a bar to order drinks. There is a variety of games to play; from fun interactive games, games that require you to move your body, to virtual reality style games. In order to play the virtual reality games you must sign a waiver and that line can be long depending on if it's busy that day or not. The other games dont require a waiver however they do require points. You can buy points or credit, whichever you wish to call it, when you first walk in. Those points will be transferred to a play card. You can use this card to play games! If you're only there to watch your friends play, you can. Admission is free< /Review>< pictures>

<user>117967620461548557611< /user><user_name>Beasley Sweets<//user_name>< Date>
1574878342675</Date>
< rate>
4<//rate>
<Review>Has great potential but on our visit some of the games were either out of order or had issues.  I was also looking forward to playing their escape room but they took it out. They have story rooms which really aren't the same thing and, according to the carnies we spoke with, required more than just two people. So currently, for our experience, it was merely an arcade.  We drove 1 1/2 hours to get there and were a bit disappointed.  For the two of us we purchased the $80 package, we were there for 5 hours, and left with $35+ still on our card.  Mostly because it was after buying the card that we found out that none of the more expensive experiences we had wanted to do were available.  So basically we just played arcade games all night.

Now, that all said, we are interested in making the long trek back sometime.  We will watch the website to see if/when they bring back more of their interactive experiences.

The food there is great and they have an impressive selection which includes some vegan options!  Not just your run-of-the-mill arcade food such as pretzels and corn dogs.  Nope.  It's actual real food. Various forms of sliders, gourmet hot dogs, ice cream sandwiches with all sorts of interesting flavors, and much much more.  I was impressed.  It didn't necessarily wow the taste buds but it wasn't bad at all and the options were very nice to have.  Oh, and the pizza looked amazing but we didn't try that (darn it).

As others have stated, the parking is very tough.  They have a very small parking lot.  There are options around such as a paid parking lot that wasn't far and there is street parking as well.  But it is a very bad neighborhood, and rather dark.  So make sure, if you have the option, to bring the junker car instead of your brand new pride and joy.

There are quite a few games that I've never seen before.  Not just the same old arcade games. There are some old favorites (Ms. Pac Man and Centipede to name a couple) and some new ones.  One of the games we kept returning to was a Connect Four in a basketball version.  That was fun.

I look forward to revisiting sometime in the distant future in the hopes that quite a few things have been updated/fixed and to use up the rest of the funds now sitting idly on my card.

Great concept, good food, just needs some attention and tweaking.  For now it's a C+ possibly a B-.<//Review><pictures>None< /pictures>< Resp>
{'time': 1574883985567, 'text': "Hi Beasley, thanks so much for your review and taking the time to visit our park!  We're sorry that some of our interactive experiences were not available at the time of your visit.  We do always make an effort to adapt/bring in new games to wow our customers.  I highly recommend heading to our website to sign up for our newsletter so you can be the first to hear about the new games we bring in! :) Stay tuned."}<//Resp>

<review>I've been here twice and both times were fun.
However the first time a lot of games were out of order, but still managed to have lots of fun because there's a lot to do (i.e., VR, trivia night, maze/escape room, drink). So I don't know if games breaking happen often .

The second time around every game was working, so maybe that first time was just an off day. Either way, plenty to do if a few machines are down.

Totally enjoyed the trivia night. Great for large groups, or even small groups. Includes a drink during the show.

If you're going to do any VR games, right away sign the waiver behind the clerk at the main entrance, and rush it to the second clerk towards the back so you can get your time slot. Every VR game goes by time slots. Every VR game has it's pricing. You cannot buy this at the front where you get the game card. You buy this separately. Yes, they take debit card.< /review><GmapID>0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02< /GmapID><user_id>104881681646932895432< /user_id><rate>5</rate>< pics>

< Text>
Really neat and fun place in a very questionable location. It is basically the Dave N Buster's of the future. There's a small collection of arcade games up front but the highlight is the collection of state of the art VR games. You put on a VR helmet and fight your way through a maze or fly like a bird or battle your friends. Besides the VR and video games, there's also a midway with a virtual collection of traditional fair games.
There's a full bar and restaurant as well. The specialty drinks are definitely unique and the price reflects that.< /Text>

< user_name>
Percival Gonzaga</user_name>
<Review>I was always a nerd, but this place transformed my friend.

Being my first time here, i didnt know what to expect (Oh, dont worry, im coming back for more). I was greeted kindly by the employees at the lobby, and with their help, i was able to nearly unlock everything in the arcade. There really is a lot to do, and one $50 card will pretty much run you the whole night (my friend and I went off one card). The currency after purchasing the game card they go by is "bits", but lets stick to the dollar value to keep things simple. The $50 card allowed us one VR Game (I let her play) and the rest was pretty much everywhere else in the Arcade - you can order food and drinks (including alcohol) off your game card, too.

They have about 3 bars throughout the venue, and they all stay open as long as the arcade is open. They also have lounge chairs along the back if you want to rest and relax, play a game of Jenga or any other game that you might have brought. On the opposite side of the lounge chairs, there are several VR stations that you can play. The games menu is readily available at the desk in the back where the associates will also help you get strapped in. Some games are playable up to 4 players, play in co-op, or single player as well. There are actually some games, too that can have up to 8 players simultaneously in one swipe.

I think $50 is already a great value, but of course you can top-up for more fun and games. The food is fairly prices with decent portions. You can just pick up a to-go box the same place where you can get condiments and utensils. There is a space to eat, and you can eat or carry your food throughout the venue. Allies are recommended with a small chance of leaving with some enemies. Avoiding sore-losers are a must, and armor isnt necessary.

You can find some parking along Mateo and Imperial street, and i recommend going on a weekday.< /Review><Resp>None< /Resp><pics>None</pics><Rating>5<//Rating><UserId.>101466442122096967700< /UserId.><GmapID>0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02< /GmapID><Time>1553911911658<//Time></record>

< Text>
What fun! My group did it all and ate it all. The escape room is good, we did the Lost City and escaped in time. The VR stuff isn't as smooth, but had fun with that. <Rating>5< /Rating><user_id>116849946697029256338<//user_id>< Gmap_id>
0x80c2c6701ba4d465:0xf7be8a5fc8bc7f02< /Gmap_id>
< Text>
I love he whole concept and plus the fact that it has a private parking lot (that is major in DTLA).
I love how there is a place where us as adults can be silly and goofy yet with a futuristic twist, also the fact that there is a bar. Alcohol always makes everything more interesting *ahaamm*
So right when we walked in there was a little booth where we got to pick how many bits we wanted. They sell them by 100, 200, 300, and so on. Each game is average 20 bits, expect for the private VR rooms which are 300 bits per person, which equals to $15.00. We decided to go with the 600 bits which was $30.00 so we'll get a chance to play freely and when we decided to do the private VR room we paid separately. All the games are so fun! There were games we played when we were kids in the arcades but these had a digital twist on them. It was cool! The best part was he private VR room. I had never experienced virtual reality so this was a huge deal for me. The mission was to protect our raft from aliens. It was scary and exhilarating all at once. It was 15 minutes long and I enjoyed every second of it. I can't wait to go back with a huge group of people</Text>

<username>Kevin Rabanales</username>< text>
The place was only half full but for some reason I ended up waiting 20 minutes for a drink. Their service is way too slow. My girlfriend wanted to order food but they didn't have everything on the menu, which made me wonder why they had a menu to begin with. They printed out a piece of paper with about 6 items on it and we were told that's all they had. Then we waited about 40 minutes for the food but by that time we were up for a story room. $40 each for about 12 minutes of mild entertainment, not worth it. The lines are too long, you don't get enough play time, they push you to buy a card as soon as you walk in. Save your money and stay away from this place. Or go in the middle of the day while it's empty.<//text>
